dir-section.heading: Regulatory and Advisory Bodies
dir-section.p: Insurance is generally regulated at the state level. However, federal oversight of the sector was strengthened through the Dodd-Frank Wall Street Reform and Consumer Protection Act of 2010, with the establishment within the Department of the Treasury of the Federal Insurance Office, to monitor all aspects of the insurance industry, and the Financial Stability Oversight Council, to identify potential risks to the financial system, including in the insurance sector.

dir-section.heading: Principal Companies
dir-section.p: In 2022 there were 5,965 insurance companies operating in the USA, including the territories. Of these, 2,484 provided property and/or casualty insurance services, 1,031 provided health insurance, and 830 provided life insurance and/or annuities.
